<DOC><DOCNO> AP900628-0027 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-90 0128EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i BC-Salvador-Shooting     06-28 0203</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Salvador-Shooting,0212</SECOND><HEAD>Salvadoran Assembly Leader Attacked By Unknown Gunman</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Attackers apparently targetingthe president of El Salvador's assembly hit one of his policeescorts with gunfire on Wednesday but no one was injured, thepolitician said.   Assembly president Ricardo Alvarenga, who was on his way homefrom the assembly, told a news conference that his car took off athigh speed when he heard the shooting.   He blamed the attack on leftist rebelsm, who have been fightinga series of U.S. backed governments for a decade.   Alvarenga lamented the shooting incident because it occurredjust two days after rightist government of President AlfredoCristiani and guerrilla leaders completed a round of peace talks inMexico.   His words at the news conference were broadcast on independentRadio YSKL.   Alvarenga, a member of Cristiani's governing Republican NationalAlliance, said he heard two or three shots lodge in one of hispolice escort's cars.   He said one police cruiser had been in front of him and one inback.   The incident happened during a rainstorm that caused a powerouttage, leaving the streets dark.   Alvarenga said the shots rang out when he was about 1.5 milesfrom the assembly.</TEXT></DOC>